{
  "doc_id": "44493",
  "text": "Physical studies have shown theoretical and experimental evidence that the DTI model has shortcomings which may limit its application in the measurement of cardiac orthotropy [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . A monoexponential diffusion model is used to analyze the raw signals leading to DTI. This model envisages a single diffusion compartment in each image voxel. Importantly, it has been demonstrated in the ventricular myocardium of ex vivo perfused hearts that there may be more than one diffusion component per voxel (i.e. multiexponential diffusion, with more than one spin compartment) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These diffusion components have been classified as a slow component (attributed to compartmentalization of intra-and extracellular (IC/EC) water pools) and a fast component (attributed to diffusion in the vascular space compartment combined with some IC diffusion) [CITATION_6] . In imaging studies with short diffusion distances (low b-values, i.e. b-value < 1000s/mm [CITATION_7] , where the b-value is defined below) the fast-component (vascular/IC) predominates, but this component still influences measurements at higher b-values. Blood vessels generally run parallel to local myocyte directions [CITATION_8] , and it has been suggested that the summation effect of slow and fast diffusion directions in the standard monoexponential DTI model is not an important practical consideration in the measurement of the local myocyte orientation. Indeed it has been shown that the local myocyte orientations calculated from the fast and slow components of diffusion are similar [CITATION_9] . However, a consequence of two-component diffusion is that the proposed orthotropic diffusion may be complicated by non-orthotropic fast diffusion which could result in inaccurate measures of laminar orientation. Limitations of the diffusion model have not been addressed to date in direct validation studies of DTI myolaminar orientation measurement [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
